value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of oxanine DNA N-glycosylase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of oxanine DNA N-glycosylase activity is decreased.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing mitomycin C.

label.value: normal double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). NHEJ is the repair of double-strand breaks in DNA in which the two broken ends are rejoined with little or no sequence complementarity.

label.value: decreased double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ) is decreased. NHEJ is the repair of double-strand breaks in DNA in which the two broken ends are rejoined with little or no sequence complementarity.
A cell phenotype in which the number of GT dinucleotide microsatellite repeats present in a sequence varies more than normal.

A molecular function phenotype in which an interaction between a protein and GU repeat regions in an RNA is decreased. One of the relevant gene products may be encoded by the mutated gene, or both the RNA and protein may be encoded by genes other than the mutated one.

A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding at microsatellite repeat regions by a gene product is decreased, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding at GT dinucleotide microsatellite repeat regions by a gene product is decreased, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
A physical cellular phenotype in which the position or morphology of all or part of the septum is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal septum organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal septum.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which a cell or hypha has a septum in an abnormal location. The normal location during yeast-form growth is at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell.

definition.value: Note that the location of the septum is determined by the location of the contractile ring, which in turn is determined by the location of the cell division site, so an abnormality in cell division site determination can be inferred from this phenotype.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell has a septum in an abnormal location when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.
A physical cellular phenotype characterized by the presence of more than one septum in a cell.
A physical cellular phenotype in which the cell contains one or more septa.
A cell phenotype in which a cell contains more than one septum when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of polynucleotide 5'-phosphatase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which polynucleotide 5'-phosphatase activity is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of an ATPase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid separation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Mitotic sister chromatid separation is the process in which sister chromatids are physically detached from each other during mitosis.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a phosphatase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which a phosphatase activity is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a phosphatase activity is decreased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of CTD phosphatase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of CTD phosphatase activity is decreased.
A spindle phenotype in which the mitotic spindle is longer than normal during metaphase.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which CENP-A-containing chromatin organization is abnormal.

label.value: normal duration of mitotic M phase

value.value: A cell cycle phenotype in which the duration of M phase of the mitotic cell cycle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal protein localization to CENP-A containing chromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to CENP-A containing chromatin is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found associated with heterochromatin and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to CENP-A containing chromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to CENP-A containing chromatin is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein localization to CENP-A containing chromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to CENP-A containing chromatin is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to CENP-A containing chromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the CENP-A containing chromatin is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount, distribution, or morphology of all or part of the microtubule cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount, distribution, or morphology of all or part of the post-anaphase array of microtubules is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array structure.

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the post-anaphase array of microtubules is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array structure.

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which cell cycle regulation mediated by the mitotic cell cycle spindle assembly checkpoint does not occur under conditions that normally trigger the checkpoint signaling and response. Normally, the mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint delays the metaphase/anaphase transition of a mitotic nuclear division until the spindle is correctly assembled and chromosomes are attached to the spindle.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a cyclin-dependent protein kinase activity is increased.
A cell phenotype in which the amount of DNA measured in a cell differs from normal.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: altered DNA level during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of DNA measured in a cell differs from normal when the cell is in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased spatial extent of CENP-A containing chromatin assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin containing the histone H3 variant CenH3 (also called CENP-A; Cnp1 in S. pombe) are assembled over a smaller portion of the centromeric region of the chromosome than normal. CENP-A-containing nucleosomes are normally assembled into chromatin at the centromeres, encompassing the central core and centromeric inner repeat regions.

label.value: increased histone H4-K16 acetylation at centromere central core during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which acetylation of lysine at position 16 of histone H4 in at the centromere central core occurs to a greater extent than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to 5-fluorouracil. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of 5-fluorouracil that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: increased duration of protein phosphorylation during cellular response to methylglyoxal

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the duration of protein phosphorylation is longer than normal during a cellular response to methylglyoxal. All phosphorylation may be affected, or only phosphorylation of specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein phosphorylation during cellular response to sorbitol

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to sorbitol.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cellular protein localization is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid separation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in regions containing ribosomal DNA (rDNA). Mitotic sister chromatid separation is the process in which sister chromatids are physically detached from each other during mitosis.

A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid separation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at telomeres. Mitotic sister chromatid separation is the process in which sister chromatids are physically detached from each other during mitosis.

label.value: normal chromatin silencing at centromere central core

value.value: A transcription regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at the centromere central core. Chromatin silencing is the observed effect of processes that repress transcription at the centromere central core, which is normally assembled into CENP-A-containing chromatin.

definition.value: Note that the centromere central core corresponds to SO:0001796. Chromatin silencing phenotypes at the centromere central core may reflect the assembly or maintenance of CENP-A-containing chromatin. See the GO cellular component term 'CENP-A containing chromatin' (GO:0061638), and the biological process term 'CENP-A containing chromatin organization' (GO:0061641).

label.value: delayed onset of protein degradation during mitosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein degradation begins later than normal during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during cellular response to hydrogen peroxide

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a greater extent than normal during a cellular response to hydrogen peroxide.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to nucleus during cellular response to hydrogen peroxide

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is increased during a cellular response to hydrogen peroxide.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
